value: Stated in the manuscript catalogues of the Stead Collection to have come from a Dresden collection.

Whole composite armour, for field or cavalry use, decorated with fluting in the Maximilian fashion. Consisting of an armet, a collar, a breast plate with skirt and tassets, a backplate with skirt, a pair of spaudlers and vambraces, a pair of gauntlets, a pair of cuisses and polyens, and a pair of greaves and sabatons.
all dated around 1510-20, except the pair of gauntlets which are probably 19th century, but in the style of about 1510-20

summary_title: The Knight and the Blast Furnace, A History of the Metallurgy of Armour in the Middle Ages and the Modern Period
notes: Publ. Illustrated, p. 613, with the microstructure consisting of ferrite, very little pearlite and slag inclusions only. Microhardness (average) is 209 VPH.
